ce:section.ce:para:
For pH sensing in living cells, to assess the imaging ability of Cu-CDs is of great importance. First, the cytotoxicity of Cu-CDs to HeLa cells was evaluated by standard MTT experiment. Over 85 % of the cells were viable with the Cu-CDs at concentrations up to 1 mg/mL as depicted in Fig. S7b, indicating low toxicity of the Cu-CDs and concluding their prospective application in biological systems. As displayed in Fig. 5
                        , the cells cultured with the Cu-CDs showed bright blue fluorescence and the Cu-CDs could be used for tracing cell. In addition, we found that the Cu-CDs can not only enter the cytoplasm, but also enter the cell nucleus. There was a great fluorescence overlap between the Cu-CDs and commercial nuclear Tracker acridine orange, and the Pearson’s correlation coefficient was 0.88. Therefore, it can be concluded that as synthesized Cu-CDs have prospective as fluorescent sensor in nuclear targeting cellular imaging. Later, we tested the capability of the Cu-CDs to estimate the fluctuation of intracellular pH in HeLa cells. The cells were cultured using the Cu-CDs at 37 °C for 30 min, and the media were taken place of with BR buffers of different pH (2.0, 4.0, 6.0). The cells clearly exhibited bright blue fluorescence at pH = 2.0. With the pH increasing to 4.0, the FL intensity slightly decreased. However, the FL intensity of HeLa cells was hardly discovered with pH at 6.0 (Fig. 6
                        ). It proved that the phenomenon of fluorescence variation in vivo was in accordance with that in vitro. The results show that the as-prepared Cu-CDs can be applied in monitoring pH variations in living cells.
